Types of Data
---------------

	INTEGER
	REAL
	TEXT

Different types of data that a user can store in a database.


Primary Keys
---------------

	PRIMARY KEY

Every table needs a primary key. Add a modifier to the columns type to specify.


Creating a New Table
------------------------

	CREATE TABLE <table_name> (<column_name> <type>, ...);

Creates a new table with a given name, and fields of types that are specified.


Inserting Into an Existing Table
-----------------------------------

	INSERT INTO <table_name> VALUES (value, ...);

Adds a new row to the end of the table with all the values that you specify. Youâ€™ll need to supply a value for each field in the table.


Selecting From a Table
--------------------------

	SELECT <column_name, ...> FROM <table_name> WHERE <statement>;

Retrieves the columns from a specified table with the conditions after the WHERE clause. That last one is optional if you want to bring back everything.


Mathematical Operators
---------------------------

	SELECT SUM(<column_name>) FROM <table_name>;

Adds up all the values in a single column.

### Counting Rows ###

	SELECT COUNT(<column_name>) FROM <table_name>;

Counts the number of values in the specified column that are non-null.

	SELECT COUNT(*) FROM <table_name>;

Counts the number of values returned by the query.

	SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT <column_name>) FROM <table_name>;

Counts the number of values in the specified column that are unique.